@SirLibraryEater One word: mulligan. I think that perhaps that someday, somewhere, somebody part of your imaginary T2 hasn't nor ever will happen as long as you have to have two mana. So I'm nitpicky and busted apart your "wow" factor comment. Sue me.
@goldwing8 First of all, this is a great place to learn about cards' strengths and weaknesses, and with that type of community comes a popular (not always varied) or several popular opinions as to the pros and cons of a particular card. In this case, you might have some difficulty finding someone who will tell you "Eh, Black Lotus sucks," or the ever incredible reply of "I don't get it. All it does is give you mana?"
Well, if you don't know or took a long time to learn like I did, let me tell you now: In Magic, mana is king. The King. I'm sure multiple, more experienced long-time players could show me multiple cards that say something like "No mana, win the game!" or who knows what else. After all, cards this good exist (but this is arguably one of the best - if not the very best - cards in the game). Why? Essentially free mana. No, you can't play the Lotus as an instant by itself, it doesn't work like the [autocard]Chromatic Lantern[/autocard], is very similar to [autocard]Gilded Lotus[/autocard] which also gives you three, but isn't sacrificed. Just think of it as a free mana bomb. For nothing, you can on your turn play a card which lets you at any time get three additional mana for whatever. Someone tries to kill your artifact? If you have an instant, play it anyway so they waste their mana. Want to be able to play a counterspell during your opponent's turn but already tapped all your mana? Black Lotus.
Anyway, if you read this, I'm sure you get the point by now. Either that or I'm terrible at anything and everything and will cry myself to sleep this Christmas outside my local magic store.

